<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	and unused lines of credit totaled $42.2 million, of which $8.3 million were at fixed rates and $33.9 million were at variable rates. We evaluate each client&#146;s credit worthiness on a case-by-case basis. The amount of collateral obtained, if deemed necessary by us upon extension of credit, is based on our credit evaluation of the borrower. The type of collateral varies but may include accounts receivable, inventory, property, plant and equipment, and commercial and residential real estate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	We had letters of credit totaling $333,000 and $1.3 million at December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively. The credit risk and collateral involved in issuing letters of credit is essentially the same as that involved in extending loan facilities to clients. Since most of the letters of credit are expected to expire without being drawn upon, they do not necessarily represent future cash requirements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Except as otherwise disclosed, we are not involved in off-balance sheet contractual relationships, unconsolidated related entities that have off-balance sheet arrangements, or transactions that could result in liquidity needs or other commitments that significantly impact earnings.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Impact of Inflation and Changing Prices
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The consolidated financial statements and related financial data presented in this filing have been prepared in accordance with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles, which require the measurement of financial position and operating results in terms of historical dollars, without considering the change in the relative purchasing power of
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	money over time due to inflation.&#160; The impact of inflation is reflected in the increased cost of the Company&#146;s operations.&#160; Unlike most industrial companies, virtually all the assets and liabilities of a financial institution are monetary in nature.&#160; As a result, interest rates generally have a more significant impact on a financial institution&#146;s performance than do general levels of inflation.&#160; Interest rates do not necessarily move in the same direction or to the same extent as the prices of goods and services
<B>
	.
</B>
</FONT>
</P>
</EFX_LIQUIDITY_CAPITAL>
</EFX_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<EFX_MARKET_RISK>
<A NAME="FIS_MARKET_RISK"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Item 7A. Quantitative and Qualitative Disclosures about Market Risk.
</FONT>
</B>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_ITEM7A_QUANTITATIVEANDQUALITATIV_124017">
</A>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Our principal financial objective is to achieve long-term profitability while reducing exposure to fluctuating market interest rates.&#160; The Company has sought to reduce the exposure of its earnings to changes in market interest rates by attempting to manage the mismatch between asset and liability maturities and interest rates.&#160; In order to reduce the exposure to interest rate fluctuations, the Company has developed strategies to manage its liquidity and shorten its effective maturities of certain interest-earning assets.&#160; We do not maintain a trading account for any class of financial instrument nor do we engage in hedging activities or purchase high-risk derivative instruments, and we are not subject to foreign exchange rate risk or commodity price risk.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	We monitor interest rate sensitivity and interest rate risk with an earnings simulation model generated by First National Bankers Bank of Louisiana who employs the Sungard Ambit ALM4 model.&#160; This model uses rate risk measurement techniques to produce a reasonable estimate of interest margin risks.&#160; The system provides several
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	60
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_60_123737_3020">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>

<A NAME="eolPage60"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	methods for measuring interest rate risk, including rate sensitivity gap analysis to show cash flow and repricing information, and margin simulation, or rate shocking, to quantify the actual income risk, by modeling the Company&#146;s sensitivity to changes in cash flows over a variety of interest rate scenarios.&#160; The program performs a full simulation of each balance sheet category under various rate change conditions and calculates the net interest income change for each.&#160; Each category&#146;s interest change is calculated as rates ramp up and down.&#160; In addition, the prepayment speeds and repricing speeds are changed.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The following illustrates the effects on net interest income of an immediate shift in market interest rates from the earnings simulation model as of December&nbsp;31, 2015:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 201
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	5
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	, our balance sheet was in an asset-sensitive position and remains in an asset sensitive position for the next four years.&#160; During the asset-sensitive time frame, an increase in interest rates would have a positive effect on earnings and a decrease in interest rates would have a negative effect on earnings.&#160; The Company&#146;s
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	interest rate risk position is also impacted by the activation of floors on variable rate loans subject to repricing during the time frame.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	In preparing the preceding table, we used certain assumptions relating to interest rates, loan prepayment rates, deposit decay rates, and the market values of certain assets under differing interest rate scenarios, among others.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	As with any method of measuring interest rate risk, certain shortcomings are inherent in the method of analysis presented in the foregoing table.&#160; For example, although certain assets and liabilities may have similar maturities or periods to repricing, they may react in different degrees to changes in market interest rates.&#160; Also, the interest rates on certain types of assets and liabilities may fluctuate in advance of changes in market interest rates, while interest rates on other types may lag behind changes in market rates.&#160; Additionally, certain assets, such as ARM loans, have features that restrict changes in interest rates on a short-term basis and over the life of the asset.&#160; Further, in the event of a change in interest rates, expected rates of prepayments on loans and early withdrawals from certificates could deviate significantly from those assumed in calculating the table.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

	Citizens First Corporation

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">
	We have audited the accompanying consolidated balance sheets of Citizens First Corporation as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the related consolidated statements of comprehensive income, changes in stockholders&#146; equity and cash flows for the years then ended.&#160; These financial statements are the responsibility of the Company&#146;s management.&#160; Our responsibility is to express an opinion on these financial statements based on our audits.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">
	We conducted our audits in accordance with the standards of the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (United States).&#160; Those standards require that we plan and perform the audit to obtain reasonable assurance about whether the financial statements are free of material misstatement.&#160; The Company is not required to have, nor were we engaged to perform, an audit of its internal control over financial reporting.&#160; Our audit included consideration of internal control over financial reporting as a basis for designing audit procedures that are appropriate in the circumstances, but not for the purpose of expressing an opinion on the effectiveness of the Company&#146;s internal control over financial reporting.&#160; Accordingly, we express no such opinion. An audit includes examining, on a test basis, evidence supporting the amounts and disclosures in the financial statements.&#160; An audit also includes assessing the accounting principles used and significant estimates made by management, as well as evaluating the overall financial statement presentation.&#160; We believe that our audits provide a reasonable basis for our opinion.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:11.0PT;">
	In our opinion, the consolidated financial statements referred to above present fairly, in all material respects, the financial position of Citizens First Corporation as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, and the results of its operations and its cash flows for the years then ended in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles.
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage67"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="4" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:14.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Note 1: Nature of Operations and Summary of Significant
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-INDENT:57.35PT;">
<B>
<FONT SIZE="4" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:14.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#160;Accounting Policies
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Nature of Operations and Principles of Consolidation
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;The consolidated financial statements include Citizens First Corporation and its wholly-owned subsidiary Citizens First Bank,&nbsp;Inc., together referred to as &#147;the Company&#148; or &#147;the Bank&#148;.&#160; Intercompany transactions and balances are eliminated in consolidation.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company provides financial services to individual and corporate customers in Warren, Simpson, Barren and Hart counties in Kentucky and central Tennessee.&#160; Its primary deposit products are checking, savings, and term certificate accounts, and its
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	primary lending products are residential mortgage, commercial and consumer loans.&#160; Substantially all loans are secured by specific items of collateral including business assets, consumer assets, and commercial and residential real estate.&#160; Commercial loans are expected to be repaid from cash flow from operations of businesses.&#160; There are no significant concentrations of loans to any one industry or customer.&#160; However, the customers&#146; ability to repay their loans is dependent on the real estate and general economic conditions in the area.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Use of Estimates
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;To prepare financial statements in conformity with U.S. generally accepted accounting principles, management makes estimates and assumptions based on available information.&#160; These estimates and assumptions affect the amounts reported in the financial statements and the disclosures provided, and actual results could differ.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Cash Flows
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Cash and cash equivalents includes cash, deposits with other financial institutions under 90 days, and federal funds sold.&#160; Net cash flows are reported for customer loan and deposit transactions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Securities
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Debt securities are classified as available for sale when they might be sold before maturity.&#160; Securities available for sale are carried at fair value, with unrealized holding gains and losses reported in other comprehensive income (loss), net of tax. Interest income includes amortization of purchase premium or discount.&#160; Premiums and discounts on securities are amortized on the level-yield method without anticipating prepayments, except for mortgage backed securities where prepayments are anticipated.&#160; Gains and losses on sales are recorded on the trade date and determined using the specific identification method.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Management evaluates securities for other-than-temporary impairment (&#147;OTTI&#148;) at least on a quarterly basis, and more frequently when economic or market conditions warrant such an evaluation.&#160; For securities in an unrealized loss position, management considers the extent and duration of the unrealized loss, and the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer. Management also assesses whether it intends to sell, or it is more likely than not that it will be required to sell, a security in an unrealized loss position before recovery of its amortized cost basis. If either of the criteria regarding intent or requirement to sell is met, the entire difference between amortized cost and fair
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	68
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_68_082644_2553">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 68',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage68"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	value is recognized as impairment through earnings. For debt securities that do not meet the aforementioned criteria, the amount of impairment is split into two components as follows: 1) OTTI related to credit loss, which must be recognized in the income statement and 2) OTTI related to other factors, which is recognized in other comprehensive income. The credit loss is defined as the difference between the present value of the cash flows expected to be collected and the amortized cost basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Loans Held for Sale
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Mortgage loans originated and intended for sale in the secondary market are carried at the lower of aggregate cost or fair value, as determined by outstanding commitments from investors.&#160; Net unrealized losses, if any, are recognized through a valuation allowance by charges to income. Gains on sales of mortgage loans
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	are recorded at the time of disbursement by an investor at the difference between the sales proceeds and the loan&#146;s carrying value. Loans are sold servicing released.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Loans
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Loans that management has the intent and ability to hold for the foreseeable future or until maturity or payoff are reported at their outstanding principal balance adjusted for any charge-offs, allowance for loan losses, any deferred fees or costs on originated loans and unamortized premiums or discounts on purchased loans.&#160; Interest income is reported on the interest method and includes amortization of net deferred loan fees and costs over the loan term on the level-yield method. Past due status is based on contractual terms of the loan. Generally, loans are placed on non-accrual status at 90 days past due and interest is considered a loss, unless the loan is well secured and in the process of collection.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	All interest accrued but not received for loans placed on nonaccrual is reversed against interest income. Interest received on such loans is accounted for on the cash-basis or cost-recovery method, until qualifying for return to accrual.&#160; Loans are returned to accrual status when all the principal and interest amounts contractually due are brought current and future payments are reasonably assured.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Allowance for Loan Losses
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;The allowance for loan losses is a valuation allowance for probable incurred credit losses. The allowance for loan losses is established as losses are estimated to have occurred through a provision for loan losses charged to income. For all loan portfolio segments, loan losses are evaluated on a case by case basis and charged against the allowance when management believes the uncollectibility of a loan balance is confirmed. Subsequent recoveries, if any, are credited to the allowance.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The allowance for loan losses is evaluated on a regular basis by management and is based upon management&#146;s periodic review of the collectability of the loans in light of historical experience, the nature and volume of the loan portfolio, adverse situations that may affect the borrower&#146;s ability to repay, estimated value of any underlying collateral, information about specific borrower situations and estimated collateral values, prevailing economic conditions, and other factors. This evaluation is inherently subjective as it requires estimates that are susceptible to significant revision as more information becomes available. Allocations of the allowance may be made for specific loans, but the
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	69
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_69_082819_5796">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 69',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage69"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	entire allowance is available for any loan that, in management&#146;s judgment, should be charged off.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The allowance consists of specific and general components. The specific component relates to loans that are individually classified as impaired. A loan is considered impaired when, based on current information and events, it is probable that the Company will be unable to collect the scheduled payments of principal or interest when due according to the contractual terms of the loan agreement.&#160; Factors considered by management in determining impairment include payment status and the probability of collecting scheduled principal and interest payments when due. Loans for which the terms have been modified resulting in a concession, and for which the borrower is experiencing financial difficulties, are considered troubled debt restructurings and classified as
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	impaired. Loans that experience insignificant payment delays and payment shortfalls generally are not classified as impaired. Management determines the significance of payment delays and payment shortfalls on a case-by-case basis, taking into consideration all of the circumstances surrounding the loan and the borrower, including the length of the delay, the reasons for the delay, the borrower&#146;s prior payment record and the amount of the shortfall in relation to the principal and interest owed.&#160; Impairment is measured on a loan-by-loan basis for all loan classes by either the present value of expected future cash flows discounted at the loan&#146;s effective interest rate, the loan&#146;s obtainable market price or the fair value of the collateral if the loan is collateral dependent.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The general component covers non-impaired loans and is based on historical loss experience adjusted for qualitative current factors. The historical loss experienced is determined by portfolio segment and is based on the actual loss history experienced by the Company over the most recent 12 quarters. This actual loss experience is supplemented with other economic factors based on the risks present for each portfolio segment. These factors can include the following:&#160; levels of and trends in delinquencies and impaired loans; levels of and trends in charge offs and recoveries; trends in volume and terms of loans; effects of any changes in risk selection and underwriting standards; other changes in lending policies, procedures, and practices; experience, ability, and depth of lending management and other relevant staff; national and local economic trends and conditions; industry conditions; and effects of changes in credit concentrations.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Troubled debt restructurings are separately identified for impairment disclosures and are measured at the present value of estimated future cash flows using the loan&#146;s effective rate at inception.&#160; If a troubled debt restructuring is considered to be a collateral dependent loan, the loan is reported, net, at the fair value of the collateral.&#160; For troubled debt restructurings that subsequently default, the Company determines the amount of reserve in accordance with the accounting policy for the allowance for loan losses.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company defines its portfolio segments by regulatory classification, which include the following:&#160; Commercial loans, consisting of loans to depository institutions, loans to
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	70
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_70_082848_2897">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 70',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage70"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	finance agricultural production, and other non-real estate commercial and industrial loans; Commercial Real Estate, consisting of loans for construction and land development, farmland, multi-family residential properties, and other non-farm, non-residential real estate loans; Residential Real Estate, consisting of first liens on residential 1-4 family properties and junior liens (revolving and non-revolving) on residential 1-4 family properties; and Consumer, including revolving and non-revolving consumer purpose loans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Commercial real estate loans may be affected to a greater extent than residential loans by adverse conditions in real estate markets or the economy because commercial real estate borrowers&#146; ability to repay their loans depends on successful development of their properties, in addition to the factors affecting residential real estate borrowers. These loans also involve greater risk because they generally are not fully amortizing over the loan period, but have a balloon payment due at maturity
</FONT>
<B>
<I>
<FONT FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	.
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Commercial loans are typically based on the borrowers&#146; ability to repay the loans from the cash flow of their businesses. These loans may involve greater risk because the availability of funds to repay each loan depends substantially on the success of the business itself. In addition, the collateral securing the loans have the following characteristics: (a)&nbsp;they depreciate over time, (b)&nbsp;they are difficult to appraise and liquidate, and (c)&nbsp;they fluctuate in value based on the success of the business. These loans are secured and unsecured and are made available for general operating inventory and accounts receivables, as well as any other purposes considered appropriate. We will generally look to a borrower&#146;s business operations as the principal source of repayment, but will also require, when appropriate, security interests in personal property and personal guarantees. In addition, the majority of commercial loans that are not mortgage loans are secured by a lien on equipment, inventory and other assets of the commercial borrower. These loans are generally considered to have greater risk than first and second mortgages on real estate because these loans may be unsecured or, if they are secured, the value of the collateral may be difficult to assess and more likely to decrease than real estate.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Risk of loss on a construction loan depends largely upon whether our initial estimate of the property&#146;s value at completion of construction equals or exceeds the cost of the property construction (including interest), the availability of permanent take-out financing, and the builder&#146;s ability to ultimately sell the property. During the construction phase, a number of factors can result in delays and cost overruns. If estimates of value are inaccurate or if actual construction costs exceed estimates, the value of the property securing the loan may be insufficient to ensure full repayment when completed through a permanent loan or by seizure of collateral.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Approximately 86.0% of our loan portfolio as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 was comprised of loans collateralized by real estate. Further adverse changes in the economy affecting values of real estate generally or in our primary market specifically could significantly impair the value of our collateral and our ability to sell the collateral upon foreclosure. The real estate collateral provides an alternate source of repayment in the event of
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	71
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_71_082925_3020">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 71',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage71"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	default by the borrower and may deteriorate in value during the time the credit is extended. If real estate values decline, it is also more likely that we would be required to increase our allowance for loan losses. If during a period of reduced real estate values we are required to liquidate the collateral securing a loan to satisfy the debt or to increase our allowance for loan losses, it could materially reduce our profitability and adversely affect our financial condition.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	We originate residential real estate mortgage loans with either fixed or variable interest rates to borrowers to purchase and refinance one-to-four family properties. Real estate mortgage loans are subject to the same general risks as other loans and are particularly sensitive to fluctuations in the value of real estate, which could negatively affect a borrower&#146;s cash flow, credit worthiness and ability to repay the loan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	We make personal loans and lines of credit available to consumers for various purposes, such as the purchase of automobiles, boats and other recreational vehicles, and the
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	making of home improvements and personal investments. Consumer loans generally have shorter terms and higher interest rates than residential mortgage loans and usually involve more credit risk than mortgage loans because of the type and nature of the collateral. Consumer lending collections are dependent on a borrower&#146;s continuing financial stability and are thus likely to be adversely affected by job loss, illness or personal bankruptcy. In many cases, repossessed collateral for a defaulted consumer loan will not provide an adequate source of repayment of the outstanding loan balance because of depreciation of the underlying collateral. We believe that the generally higher yields earned on consumer loans help compensate for the increased credit risk associated with such loans and that consumer loans are important to our efforts to serve the credit needs of our customer base.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Federal Home Loan Bank (FHLB) Stock
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;The Bank is a member of the FHLB system.&#160; Members are required to own a certain amount of stock based on the level of borrowings and other factors, and may invest in additional amounts.&#160; FHLB stock is carried at cost, classified as a restricted security, and periodically evaluated for impairment based on ultimate recovery of par value.&#160; Both cash and stock dividends are reported as income.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Premises and Equipment
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Land is carried at cost.&#160; Premises and equipment are stated at cost less accumulated depreciation.&#160; Buildings and related components are depreciated using the straight-line method with useful lives ranging from twenty-five to forty years.&#160;&#160; Leasehold improvements are amortized over the shorter of the life of the lease or the life of the asset.&#160; Furniture, fixtures and equipment are depreciated using the straight-line with useful lives ranging from three to seven years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Foreclosed Assets&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Assets acquired through, or in lieu of, loan foreclosure are held for sale and are initially recorded at fair value, less costs to sell, at the date of foreclosure, establishing a new cost basis. Physical possession of residential real estate property collateralizing a consumer mortgage loan occurs when legal title is obtained upon completion of foreclosure or when the borrower conveys all interest in the property to
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	72
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_72_083024_7748">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 72',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage72"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	satisfy the loan through completion of a deed in lieu of foreclosure or through a similar legal agreement. These assets are subsequently accounted for at a lower of cost of fair value less estimated costs to sell. Subsequent to foreclosure, valuations are periodically performed by management to validate the carrying value of the foreclosed properties.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Bank Owned Life Insurance
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Bank has purchased life insurance policies on certain key employees.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Bank owned life insurance is recorded at the amount that can be realized under the insurance contract at the balance sheet date, which is the cash surrender value adjusted for other charges or other amounts due that are probable at settlement.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Goodwill and Other Intangible Assets&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Prior to January&nbsp;1, 2009
<B>
<I STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	,
</I>
</B>
	goodwill resulted from business acquisitions and represented the excess of the purchase price over the fair value of acquired tangible assets and liabilities and identifiable intangible assets.&#160; Goodwill resulting from business combinations after January&nbsp;1, 2009, is generally determined as the excess of the fair value of the consideration transferred, plus the fair value of the net assets acquired and liabilities assumed as of the acquisition date.
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Goodwill is tested annually for impairment.&#160; If the implied fair value of goodwill is lower than its carrying amount, goodwill impairment is indicated and goodwill is written down to its implied fair value in the period identified.&#160; The Company has selected December&nbsp;31 as the date to perform the annual impairment test. The Company&#146;s assessment did not identify impairment of goodwill as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014.&#160; The balance of goodwill was $4.1 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Other intangible assets consist largely of core deposit intangible assets arising from a bank acquisition.&#160; They are initially measured at fair value and then are amortized on an accelerated method over their estimated useful lives of 8 years.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Loan Commitments and Related Financial Instruments&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Financial instruments include off-balance sheet credit instruments, such as commitments to make loans and commercial letters of credit, issued to meet customer financing needs.&#160; The face amount for these items represents the exposure to loss, before considering customer collateral or ability to repay.&#160; Such financial instruments are recorded when they are funded.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Income Taxes
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Income tax expense is the total of the current year income tax due or refundable and the change in deferred tax assets and liabilities.&#160; Deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized for the tax effects of differences between the financial statement and tax bases of assets and liabilities.&#160; A valuation allowance is established to reduce deferred tax assets if it is more likely than not that a deferred tax asset will not be realized.&#160; The Company files consolidated income tax returns with its subsidiary.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	A tax position is recognized as a benefit only if it is &#147;more likely than not&#148; that the tax position would be sustained in a tax examination, with a tax examination being presumed to occur.&#160; The amount recognized is the largest amount of tax benefit that is
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	73
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_73_083118_141">
</A>
</P>
<DIV STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">
</DIV>
</DIV>
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='PAGE 73',FILE='C:\JMS\107536\15-23235-1\TASK7851599\23235-1-GS.HTM',USER='107536',CD='MAR 22 16:11 2016' -->
<A NAME="eolPage73"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	greater than 50% likely of being realized on examination.&#160; For tax positions not meeting the &#147;more likely than not&#148; test, no tax benefit is recorded.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company recognizes interest related to income tax matters as interest expense and penalties related to income tax matters as other expense.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Stock Based Compensation Plans
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Compensation cost is recognized for performance share units issued to employees, based on the fair value of these awards at the date of grant. Compensation cost is recognized over the required service period, generally defined as the vesting period.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Retirement Plans
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Employee 401(k)&nbsp;expense is the amount of matching contributions.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Operating Segments&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	While the chief decision-makers monitor the revenue streams of the various products and services, operations are managed and financial performance is evaluated on a Company-wide basis.&#160; Operating segments are aggregated into one as operating results for all segments are similar.&#160; Accordingly, all of the financial service operations are considered by management to be aggregated in one reportable operating segment.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Earnings per Common Share&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Basic earnings per common share is net income available to common stockholders divided by the weighted average number of common shares outstanding during the period.&#160; Diluted earnings per common share include the dilutive effect of additional potential common shares issuable under stock options, performance share units, warrants and preferred stock.&#160; Earnings and dividends per share are restated for all stock splits and stock dividends through the date of issuance of the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Comprehensive Income (Loss)&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Comprehensive income consists of net income and other comprehensive income (loss).&#160; Other comprehensive income (loss) includes unrealized gains and losses on securities available for sale which are also recognized as a separate component of equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Loss Contingencies
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Loss contingencies, including claims and legal actions arising in the ordinary course of business, are recorded as liabilities when the likelihood of loss is probable and an amount or range of loss can be reasonably estimated.&#160; Management does not believe there now are such matters that will have a material effect on the financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Dividend Restriction
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Banking regulations require maintaining certain capital levels and may limit the dividends paid by the bank to the holding company or by the holding company to shareholders.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Fair Value of Financial Instruments
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Fair values of financial instruments are estimated using relevant market information and other assumptions, as more fully disclosed in a separate note.&#160; Fair value estimates involve uncertainties and matters of significant
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	74
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_74_083255_7608">
</A>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	judgment regarding interest rates, credit risk, prepayments, and other factors, especially in the absence of broad markets for particular items.&#160; Changes in assumptions or in market conditions could significantly affect the estimates.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Recent Accounting Pronouncements
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#150;
</FONT>
</I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	In May&nbsp;2014 the FASB amended existing guidance related to revenue from contracts with customers. This amendment supersedes and replaces nearly all existing revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance, establishes a new control-based revenue recognition model, changes the basis for deciding when revenue is recognized over time or at a point in time, provides new and more detailed guidance on specific topics and expands and improves disclosures about revenue. In addition, this amendment specifies the accounting for some costs to obtain or fulfill a contract with a customer. These amendments are effective for annual reporting periods beginning after December&nbsp;15, 2017, including interim periods within that reporting period. The Bank is currently evaluating the impact of this new accounting standard on the consolidated financial statements.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Reclassifications
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&#150;Certain reclassifications have been made to the 2014 financial statements to conform to the 2015 financial statement presentation. Reclassifications had no effect on prior year net income or shareholders&#146; equity.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">

</FONT>

</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:1.5%;">
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:1.0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</B>
</P>
</TD>
<TD WIDTH="13%" COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:13.24%;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="4" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:13.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Other-Than-Temporary-Impairment
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Management evaluates securities for other-than-temporary impairment (&#147;OTTI&#148;) at least on a quarterly basis, and more frequently when economic or market conditions warrant such an evaluation.&#160; Investment securities classified as available for sale are generally evaluated for OTTI under ASC Topic 320, &#147;Investments - Debt and Equity Securities.&#148;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	In determining OTTI under the ASC Topic 320 model, management considers many factors, including: (1)&nbsp;the length of time and the extent to which the fair value has been less than cost, (2)&nbsp;the financial condition and near-term prospects of the issuer, (3)&nbsp;whether the market decline was affected by macroeconomic conditions, and (4)&nbsp;whether the entity has the intent to sell the debt security or more likely than not will be required to sell the debt security before its anticipated recovery.&#160; The assessment of whether an other than temporary decline exists involves a high degree of subjectivity and judgment and is based on the information available to management at a point in time.
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	78
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_78_131747_5335">
</A>
</P>

<HR SIZE="3" WIDTH="100%" NOSHADE ALIGN="LEFT" STYLE="COLOR:#010101;">

	&nbsp;

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	As of December&nbsp;31, 2015, the Company&#146;s security portfolio consisted of $60.2 million fair value of securities, $16.2 million, or 26 securities, of which were in an unrealized loss position.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	All rated securities are investment grade.&#160; For those that are not rated, the financial condition has been evaluated and no adverse conditions were identified related to repayment.&#160; Declines in fair value are a function of rate differences in the market and market illiquidity.&#160; The Company does not intend or is not expected to be required to sell these securities before recovery of their amortized cost basis.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" COLOR="BLACK" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company&#146;s unrealized losses 12 months or more relate primarily to its investment in a single trust preferred security.&#160; The security is a single-issuer trust preferred that is not rated.&#160;
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	No impairment charge is being taken as no loss of principal or interest is anticipated.&#160; All principal and interest payments are being received as scheduled.
<FONT COLOR="BLACK" STYLE="COLOR:BLACK;">
	&#160; On a quarterly basis, we evaluate the creditworthiness of the issuer, a bank holding company with operations in the state of Kentucky.&#160; Based on the issuer&#146;s continued profitability and well-capitalized position, we do not deem that there is credit loss.&#160; The decline in fair value is primarily attributable to illiquidity affecting these markets and not the expected cash flows of the individual securities.&#160; We have evaluated the financial condition and near term prospects of the issuer and expect to fully recover our cost basis.&#160; This security continues to pay interest as agreed and future payments are expected to be made as agreed.&#160; This security is not considered to be other-than-temporarily impaired.
</FONT>
</FONT>
</P>

	The following table presents information related to impaired loans by class of loans as of and for the years ended December&nbsp;31, 2015, and 2014.&#160; In this table presentation the unpaid principal balance of the loans has not been reduced by partial net charge-offs. <P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Nonaccrual loans and loans past due 90 days still on accrual include both smaller balance homogeneous loans that are collectively evaluated for impairment and individually classified impaired loans.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The following tables present the recorded investment in nonaccrual and loans past due over 90 days still on accrual by class of loans as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and December&nbsp;31, 2014:
</FONT>
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Troubled Debt Restructurings:
</FONT>
</I>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company reported total troubled debt restructurings of $2.5 million and $4.4 million as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&#160; The Company has no commitments to lend additional amounts as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 to customers with outstanding loans that are classified as troubled debt restructurings.&#160; Troubled debt restructurings are evaluated along with other impaired loans.&#160; All 11 loans reported as troubled debt restructurings (TDRs) were on accrual status at December&nbsp;31, 2015.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	During the years ending December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014, the terms of certain loans were modified as troubled debt restructurings.&#160; The modification of the terms of such loans included one or a combination of the following: a reduction of the stated interest rate of the loan; an extension of the maturity date at a stated rate of interest lower than the current market rate for new debt with similar risk. No troubled debt restructurings were charged off during 2015 or 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">

<TD WIDTH="2%" VALIGN="BOTTOM" STYLE="PADDING:0IN 0IN 0IN 0IN;WIDTH:2.02%;">

<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The troubled debt restructurings described above had no effect on the allowance for loan losses and resulted in no charge-offs during the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2015. The troubled debt restructurings described above increased the allowance for loan losses by $1,000 and resulted in no charge-offs during the year ending December&nbsp;31, 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Specific allocations of $235,000 and $547,000 were reported for troubled debt restructurings as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The terms of certain other loans were modified during the years ending December&nbsp;31, 2015 and 2014 that did not meet the definition of a troubled debt restructuring.&#160; These loans have a total recorded investment as of December&nbsp;31, 2015 of $21.3 million and December&nbsp;31, 2014 of $13.9 million.&#160; The modification of these loans involved either a modification of the terms of a loan to borrowers who were not experiencing financial difficulties or a delay in a payment that was considered to be insignificant.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	In order to determine whether a borrower is experiencing financial difficulty, an evaluation is performed of the probability that the borrower will be in payment default on any of its debt in the foreseeable future without the modification. This evaluation is performed under the company&#146;s internal underwriting policy.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>

<A NAME="eolPage85"></A>
<BR CLEAR="ALL" STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-BEFORE:ALWAYS;">
<DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
<A HREF="#A15-23235_110K_HTM_TABLEOFCONTENTS" TITLE="CLICK TO GO TO TABLE OF CONTENTS">
<FONT FACE="ARIAL">
	Table of Contents
</FONT>
</A>
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<B>
<I>
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;">
	Credit Quality Indicators:
</FONT>
</I>
</B>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	The Company categorizes loans into risk categories based on relevant information about the ability of borrowers to service their debt such as current financial information, historical payment experience, credit documentation, public information, and current economic trends, among other factors.&#160; The Company analyzes loans individually by classifying the loans as to credit risk. This analysis includes commercial and commercial real estate loans with an outstanding balance greater than $25 thousand and is reviewed on a monthly basis. For residential real estate and consumer loans the analysis primarily involves monitoring the past due status of these loans and at such time that these loans are past due, the Company evaluates the loans to determine if a change in risk category is warranted. The Company uses the following definitions for risk ratings:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Special Mention. Loans classified as special mention have a potential weakness that deserves management&#146;s close attention. If left uncorrected, these potential weaknesses may result in deterioration of the repayment prospects for the loan or of the institution&#146;s credit position at some future date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Substandard. Loans classified as substandard are inadequately protected by the current net worth and paying capacity of the obligor or of the collateral pledged, if any. Loans so classified have a well-defined weakness or weaknesses that jeopardize the liquidation of the debt. They are characterized by the distinct possibility that the institution will sustain some loss if the deficiencies are not corrected.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Doubtful.&#160; Loans classified as doubtful have all the weaknesses inherent in those classified as substandard, with the added characteristic that the weaknesses make collection or liquidation in full, on the basis of currently existing facts, conditions, and values, highly questionable and improbable.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;">
<FONT SIZE="3" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:12.0PT;">
	Loans not meeting the criteria above that are analyzed individually as part of the above described process are considered to be Pass rated loans.&#160; All loans in all loan categories are assigned risk ratings. As of December&nbsp;31, 2015 and December&nbsp;31, 2014, and based on the most recent analysis performed, the risk category of loans by class of loans were as follows:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="TIMES NEW ROMAN" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:10.0PT;">
	&nbsp;
</FONT>
</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="MARGIN:0IN 0IN .0001PT;TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;">
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	Page
</FONT>
<FONT SIZE="1" FACE="ARIAL" STYLE="FONT-SIZE:9.0PT;">
	86
</FONT>
<A NAME="A15-23235_110K_HTM_PB_86_123815_5786">
</A>
</P>

	At December&nbsp;31, 2015, the balance of real estate owned includes no foreclosed residential real estate properties recorded as a result of obtaining physical possession of the property.&nbsp; At December&nbsp;31, 2015, there is no recorded investment of consumer
